abstract = {We evaluate how hotspots of different types of extreme summertime heat change under global warming increase of up to {\$}{\$}4$\backslash$,{\^{}}$\backslash$circ $\backslash$hbox {\{}C{\}}{\$}{\$} 4 ∘ C ; and which level of global warming allows us to avert the risk of these hotspots considering the irreducible range of possibilities defined by well-sampled internal variability. We use large samples of low-probability extremes simulated by the 100-member Max Planck Institute Grand Ensemble (MPI-GE) for five metrics of extreme heat: maximum absolute temperatures, return periods of extreme temperatures, maximum temperature variability, sustained tropical nights, and wet bulb temperatures. At {\$}{\$}2$\backslash$,{\^{}}$\backslash$circ $\backslash$hbox {\{}C{\}}{\$}{\$} 2 ∘ C of warming, MPI-GE projects maximum summer temperatures below {\$}{\$}50$\backslash$,{\^{}}$\backslash$circ $\backslash$hbox {\{}C{\}}{\$}{\$} 50 ∘ C over most of the world. Beyond {\$}{\$}2$\backslash$,{\^{}}$\backslash$circ $\backslash$hbox {\{}C{\}}{\$}{\$} 2 ∘ C , this threshold is overshot in all continents, with the maximum projected temperatures in hotspots over the Arabic Peninsula. Extreme 1-in-100-years pre-industrial temperatures occur every 10–25 years already at {\$}{\$}1.5$\backslash$,{\^{}}$\backslash$circ $\backslash$hbox {\{}C{\}}{\$}{\$} 1.5 ∘ C of warming. At {\$}{\$}4$\backslash$,{\^{}}$\backslash$circ $\backslash$hbox {\{}C{\}}{\$}{\$} 4 ∘ C , these 1-in-100-years extremes are projected to occur every 1 to 2 years over most of the world. The range of maximum temperature variability increases by 10–50{\%} at {\$}{\$}2$\backslash$,{\^{}}$\backslash$circ $\backslash$hbox {\{}C{\}}{\$}{\$} 2 ∘ C of warming, and by 50–100{\%} at {\$}{\$}4$\backslash$,{\^{}}$\backslash$circ $\backslash$hbox {\{}C{\}}{\$}{\$} 4 ∘ C . Beyond {\$}{\$}2$\backslash$,{\^{}}$\backslash$circ $\backslash$hbox {\{}C{\}}{\$}{\$} 2 ∘ C , heat stress is aggravated substantially over non-adapted area